liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Israel's Ambassador to Australia Amir Maimon has said he has received calls from PM Anthony Albanese, Foreign Minister Penny Wong and others. "More than 350 innocent lives have already been lost, and I mourn the death of a member of my own family," he wrote on social media. He expressed "deepest thanks" to the PM, Senator Wong, Peter Duton, Victorian Premier Jacinta Allan and SA Premier Peter Malinauskas. "I know they speak for millions of Australians and friends of Israel," he said. "These are terrible, dark days for my country. Now we have the grim task of finishing a fight we did not seek, and did not start. We will spare no effort in defending our homeland."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Israeli Ambassador: 'These are terrible, dark days'

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Israel's military said one its drones struck a Hezbollah post in the area of Har Dov, an area in Shebaa Farms. "At this point, there is no further threat in Har Dov or the northern arena," IDF spokesman Daniel Hagari said in televised remarks. He added the military remained on high alert. The IDF later said that it fired a warning shot toward a number of "suspects" in the same area in Har Dov. Reuters

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Carnegie Middle East Center's senior associate Yezid Sayigh has told the ABC the current conflict will likely push Israel to "really hard thinking about the long term". "I think that some sort of process is going to come out of this, what exactly that is, is very difficult to see," he said. "And that's why I imagine Hamas has a gradated list of objectives. If they've got hostages they're going to negotiate really hard, they're going to milk that for all it's worth. "But the Israeli government has hard choices (to make)." He added there may be "big change in Israel coming which could enable different kinds of politics in relation to Gaza".
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Expert predicts 'hard choices' for Israeli government

children.content: The Carnegie Middle East Center's senior associate Yezid Sayigh has told the ABC the current conflict will likely push Israel to "really hard thinking about the long term".
"I think that some sort of process is going to come out of this, what exactly that is, is very difficult to see," he said.
"And that's why I imagine Hamas has a gradated list of objectives. If they've got hostages they're going to negotiate really hard, they're going to milk that for all it's worth.
"But the Israeli government has hard choices (to make)."
He added there may be "big change in Israel coming which could enable different kinds of politics in relation to Gaza".
